1. Why did you use inheritance?

I used inheritance because all of the transport objects are vehicles. Instead of writing the same code many times, I created a base class called **Vehicle** and let **Car**, **Airplane**, **Boat**, and **Helicopter** inherit from it. 
This made the code more organized and easier to manage. It also allowed all of the vehicles to share the same `Move()` method while having different behaviors.

2. Why did you use interfaces?

I used interfaces because they describe what a class can do. For example, a car can drive, an airplane can fly, and a boat can sail. 
The interfaces `IDriveable`, `IFlyable`, and `ISailable` help separate these abilities from the vehicle itself. This makes the program more flexible and easier to expand in the future.

3. Can Helicopter inherit from both Vehicle and Airplane? Why or why not?

No. A helicopter cannot inherit from both `Vehicle` and `Airplane` because C# only allows a class to inherit from one base class. 
This is called single inheritance. A helicopter can inherit from `Vehicle` and then implement multiple interfaces, such as `IFlyable` and `IDriveable`, to have more than one ability.

4. Why can Helicopter implement both IFlyable and IDriveable?

A helicopter can implement both interfaces because interfaces only describe abilities. A helicopter can fly, so it implements `IFlyable`. 
It can also drive or move on the ground in this activity, so it implements `IDriveable`. In C#, a class can implement many interfaces at the same time.

5. If a Submarine can both sail and dive, how would you design it?

I would create a `Submarine` class that inherits from `Vehicle`. Then I would make it implement the `ISailable` interface and create another interface called `IDiveable`. 
This way, the submarine can sail on the water and dive underwater. Using interfaces makes it easy to add more abilities without changing the base `Vehicle` class.
